<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900717-0121</DOCNO><DOCID>900717-0121.</DOCID><HL>   Alcoa Posts 43% Drop   In 2nd-Quarter Profit   On Lower Ingot Prices</HL><DATE>07/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AA</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)ALUMINUM (ALU)</IN><LP>   PITTSBURGH -- Aluminum Co. of America, hurt by sharplylower aluminum ingot prices, reported that second-quarterearnings fell 43% to $161.9 million, or $1.86 a share.   A year earlier, Alcoa earned $285.2 million, or $3.21 ashare. Sales for the quarter fell slightly to $2.69 billionfrom $2.76 billion in the 1989 second quarter.</LP><TEXT>   The results, which were in line with analysts'expectations, reflect a 24% drop in aluminum ingot prices,Alcoa said.   In addition, the results reflected revenue of only $6million from the company's Brazilian affiliate, down from $61million for the first half of 1989. The drop is linked toactions taken by Brazil's government to improve thatcountry's economy. Lower fabricated activity also depressedearnings.   For the six months, Alcoa reported earnings of $310.5million, or $3.55 a share, down from $561.2 million, or $6.33a share, a year ago. Sales were $5.33 billion, down from$5.38 billion.   Earnings for the 1990 second quarter include favorabletranslation and exchange adjustments of $9.9 million, or 11cents a share, compared with $19.7 million, or 22 cents ashare, in the quarter the previous year. For the six months,the favorable adjustments were $5.8 million, or seven cents ashare, compared with $20.9 million, or 24 cents a share, in1989.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, Alcoa closedat $69.25, up 50 cents.</TEXT></DOC>